{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958032801/0216.xml":{"full_text":"66\nInquiring\nReporter\nWhy shouid we ha union members he inter\nested in politics?\u201d\ny\n\nt\nJ\neeart\ni\nDavis\n\nHigh\nNellie Davis, Holland: \u201cEvery\nthing that the government does\nis our business because it is our\nmoney that they spend which\nwe pay in taxes.\nIf we want\nthe country to be strong and if\nwe want to get the most for our\nmoney we\nmust be interested\nand get the right men elected\nto office who will serve the\npeople.\u201d\nMargarette High, 3936 Lock\nwood: \"Well, people who work\nfor a living should be interested\nin politics because taxes and un\nemployment affect them. We\nmust see to it that the right men\nare\nelected or we have no right\nto gripe when things go wrong.\u201d\n3\nZaborski\n4\nOliver\nRobert Zaborski, 1438 Leith:\n\u201cPeople should be interested in\ngovernment affairs and know\nwhat the various bills that are\nbeing introduced will do for or\nagainst them. Everyone should\nalso discuss politics freely at\ntheir meetings so that all will un\nderstand the issues in which they\nwill be confronted with in the,\nfuture.\u201d\nJames Oliver, 5726 Stephan\n\u201cThe reason people should be in\nterested in politics is because by\nnow they should have a bellyful\nof the broken promises of the\npresent administration. We have\nbad six years of this administra\ntion and it is time everyone gets\ninterested and elects men who\nwill find a way to keep the peo\npie working so that they can buy\nthe goods we all produce.\u201d\nKozlowski\nd\n\n\u2022k\nKwiatkowski\nA\n\nAlfred Kozlowski, 708 Ranch:\n\u201cIf people would get interested\nthey would learn how the candi\ndates voted for the bills that\nwere passed and in this way they\nwould know who is for them.\nToo many people listen to others\nand don't read the papers and\nmake up their own minds. Read\nall the facts to get informed and\nthen vote intelligently is what\nthe worker should do.\"\nTOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL\nTrading Post\nRates: 10 c*nt\u00bb a lint (5 unrili), minimum 2 lin\u00abn^ 80\netnlt. Mail with cath or bring in to Room 203, 425 W in\nthrop Straet, CH. i-0126, txlention 33.\nFuneral Directors\nDAY-EDWARDS MORTUARY\n741 W. Central Ave.\nCH. 4-0731\nHOEFLINGER MORTUARY\n201 Platt St.\nox. 1-6768\nFOTH MORTUARY\n2310 Jefferson Ave.\nCH 1*3241\nABELE FUNERAL HOME\n1910 Cherry St.\nLH 1-5181\nPARKS D EMMERT FUNERAL HOME\n3883 Monroe St\nGR. 2-2119\nH H. BIRKENKAMP FUNERAL\nHOMES\u20141003 Broadway\nTRILBY, Ohio. GR. 4*3772\nCH 3*2183\nBROWN FUNERAL HOME\n919 Grand Ave\nCH 2-8423\nMiscellaneous\nTOR KALE: McGuffey*\nEclectic\nSpeller. Call Grand Rapid* 21137\nElectric Tappen Range\u2014 Excellent con\ndition. GR. 0*2983 before 10 00 a.m.\u2014\nafter 4:00 pm.\nRECONDITIONED\nVacuums,\n1-year\nservice guarantee. Hoover with alt.\nS10 95. Electrolux, G. E.. Westinghouse,\nLewyt, Apex. Kirby, Eureka, Filter\nQueen, Airway, Rexaire.\nKenmore.\nFree Home Demonstration. Call CH.\n1-0159. Electro Hygiene Co., 2503 CoJ*\nlingwood.\nGerald Kwiatkowski, 2035\nMiles: \"To have good govern\nment the people must be inter-;\nested in it. With the anti-labor\u2019\nbills being introduced the work\ner must start voting or we will\nbe back to what it was 20 years\nago. People must get interested\nnow because it will be too late\nafter the union gets crippled by\nanti-labor bills.\"\nLeo Bieniek, 1136 Bucking-l\nham: \"The reason we should all\nbe interested in politics is to\nkeep what gains the old timers\nbled and died to get so we would\nhave a better life. If we don't do\nour duty as good citizens we\nhave wasted all the good that\nother union\ndone.\u201d\nmembers\nhave\nGrajczyk\n\nBieniek\nFrank Grajczyk, 1255 Blum:\nThe time is getting short be\ncause the anti-labor forces are\nhard at work to destroy all our\ngains. The young men and wom\nen don't remember or know how\nit was back 20 or 25 years ago.\nThey should read our history to\nbecome informed. That would\nget them interested in politics\nand help elect good candidates.\u201d'\nAmerican Floor\nSweepings\nBy NORM WITHERELL\nOur next regular Unit meeting\nwill be held on Thursday, April\n,3rd, in parlor B, on the second\nfloor. The current status of our\ncontract negotiations will be dis\ncussed it is very important that\nyou be there.\nAugust \u201cBarney\"\nKranz\nis\nrecuperating from a very bad\nhernia operation. Did you get\nour\n\"get well\"\ncard, Barney?\n\nHow about that\u2019\u2019\nCloyee Clark\u2019s father ia also\n1 recovering from an operation for\ngall stores, and the Clark family\nwish to thank the blood donor*\nfor their part in his recovery.\nWe are very sorry to hear that\nRalph Douglas will be unable to\nreturn to work after undergoing\na double hernia operation last\nFall The doctor says he will\nnever be able to work again, but\ndoctors can be wrong and\nwe\n1 hope this one is. Come in and\nsee us. Doug.\nIn I he Blade on March 25th,\nit was reported that the Ameri\ncan Lincoln Corp acquired the\nWilshire Power Sweeper Co., in\nGlendale, California. Our \"fami\nly\u201d is growing, and fast. Look\nout, G.M.! Don't say, I didn\u2019t\nwarn you. You might be next.\nAre you registered? Will you\nbe able to vote next November?\nThe deadline for registering was\nMarch 26th. Will you be able to\ndo your\nshare\nin\nthe fight\na g a i n s t anti-labor legislation\nwhen the time comes? If not,\ndon't blame us if we lose the\nfight. It is your fight too.\nFOR\nsed\nCurs\nSALF.\neep Station\n4-wheel drive (all CH. 2-0071.\nWagona\nService\nUNCLE JOHN S Food Co., catering to\nparties and banquets RA 6-1110\nGERRFR CABINET SHOP\u2014Specialist\nin kitchen remodeling CH. 2-9337.\nPAY water, ga*. phone. light bills at\nLocal 12 dlues window.\nMail your Salva Tax Stamps to F.\nReno. 425 Winthrop St.\nNEW YORK Lite Insurance Co. Rich\nard C. Duftey Agent. CH. 8-6481.\nHall For Rent\u2014Kitchen facilities, 3013\nDetroit near Central. CH 6-4806.\"\nCOTTON SHAG RUGS washed, dried,\ndyed re-rubberized 3-Hour service\non most rugs. Friendly Laundrymat,\n3644 Upton Ave GR. 4-6096.\nFlint Trees Shrubbery trimmed,\nsprayed. CH. 3-1934.\nTelevision Sets\nTV SET. Home appliances all types.\n1854 W. Central Ave.\nHardware Supplies\nPAINTS all kinds, low prices. Colon\nial Hardware. 1854 Central.\nla there eomothing you no longer need and would like\nto five away to help tome other union member? fuel call\nour \u201cGive Auay Column,\u201d CHwry 1-9126, Ext. 33.\n4\nCouncil Approves Citizens Group\nSeeking Settlement at Lasalle\u2018s\ni\nThe 126-day-old Lasalle strike\nis now a matter for official city\naction.\nCity Council voted Monday\nto establish a citizens\u2019 commit\ntee which will be assigned the\njob of seeking a settlement to\nthe dispute.\nThe Committee will not be\nrestricted by the rules govern\ning the LMC.\nBoth Mayor John Yager and;\nVice Mayor Ollie Czelusta ap-.\nCouncil Asks\nJobless Aid\nIn Fostoria\nFOSTORIA\u2014Acting at the re\nquest of organized labor, the\nFostoria City Council, composed\nchiefly of Republicans, passed a\nresolution urging President Ei-:\nsenhower and Ohio Governor\nO'Neill to take action to curb the\nrecession and put people back to\nwork.\nThe President was called upon\nby the resolution to take the nec\nessary steps to maintain maxi\nmum employment, production\nand purchasing power. Recom-1\nmended was a public works\u2019 pro\ngram.\nThe resolution also called\nupon Governor O\u2019Neill to take\naction to raise unemployment\nbenefits and extend them to 39\nweeks, and to permit payment of\nSupplemental U n e m p l oyment\nBenefits negotiated between\nmanagement and unions.\nC. A. (Whitey) Roser, of Elec\ntric Auto-Lite Local 533, said\nthat SUB payments for workers!\n1 in his plant totaled about $10,000\nand such payments would bene\nfit merchants as well as laid-off\nworkers.\nOther plants eligible for such\npayments, labor spokesmen said,\nin Fostoria include Ex-Cell-O\nand the Auto-Lite Foundry.\ni\nCouncilman Wayne Norris\nquestioned the right of the state\nto intervene in holding up SUB\npayments and said officials in\ngovernment should have no con\n1 trol over agreements reached by\nmanagement and labor.\nPreviously, a resolution sim\nilar to this had been passed by\nToledo City Council.\nproved the action as did the LMC\nSteering Committee.\nAt the LMC Steering Commit\ntee meeting, IBEW Local 245\nBusiness Representative George\nThomas, and the Textilework\ners\u2019 Kenneth DeLong, released a\nstatement condemning Retail As\nsociates for their union-busting\nefforts.\nThey said in part:\n\u201cIt appears to us that all stra\ntegy in the Toledo department\nstore labor strife is being\nplanned in New York, not local\nly. It also seems to be evident to\nus that the R. H. Macy Company,\nin the Toledo strike, has resorted\nto every union-busting tactic\nwhich the New York firm ever'\nbought from Nathan Sheffer\nman.\n\u201cWe have gone along hoping\nthat the strike could be settled\namicably, but by now it must\nbe apparent to the most optimis-.\ntic member of L-M-C that Re\ntail Associates has no intentions\nof bargaining with the Retail\nClerks Union.\n\"On Tuesday of last week,\nthe Retail Associates, through\ntheir attorney, presented the\nL-M-C a lengthy letter in which\nit- was stated that it would be\nimproper and illegal for the\nstores to enter into a contract\nwith the union while legal ac\ntion is pending before the NLRB\n\"We don\u2019t recall the stores\never questioning the propriety\nof entering into contracts with\nthe Retail Clerks Union the last\n20 years.\n\u201cActually, that four-page let\nter was a fraud and an irult to.\neach member of L-M-C.\n\"This is not an appeal to any\nbody's emotions\u2014the time for\nthat may have passed\u2014but we\nknow that all of the L-M-C mem\nbers are aware that the majority\nof the pickets at Lasalle's are\nwomen.\n\"We cannot see their gallant\nefforts in this strike go for\nnaught.\n\"The only action we can take\nin clear conscience is to state\nthat never could we agree to any\nsettlement terms which would\nnot restore those women to their\njobs.\n\u201cTherefore, it is our position\nthat we must insist on:\n1. A one-year contract be\ntween Retail Associates, repre\nsenting Lasalle's, Lamson's and\nThe Lion Store, and the Retail\nClerks Union.\n2. Full retroactive pay to the\n1\nLet ERIKSEN'S\nBe Your Hoadquortors For:\nOFFICE EQUIPMENT 1 SUPPLIES\n4\nU\ni\n\nk ERIKSEN S, INC.\ni\nI\nI\n323 Erie Etreet\nCH -1193\n21\nAUTO SERVICE\nAND REPAIRS\n%s\ns\nGw\nhnd\ntate\n\n92\nC\nX\n\"ARt\n\"There's a Terrible Scraping and Screeching Noise Somewhere\nI in the Rear of This Car!\"\ni Kemp Jackson Gulf Service\nDETROIT at OAKWOOD CH. 3-0684\nClem\u2019s Marathon Service\n1\nI\nU\nDETROIT at PHILLIPS\nGR. 2-0342\nMiller\u2019s Pure Oil Service\nI\nBERDAN at HAVERHILL\nGR. 5-758)\nI\nHerb\u2019s Gulf Service\nCOLLINGWOOD at ASHLAND\nTony\u2019s Gulf Service\nDETROIT at LAWRENCE\ni\ni\nI\n\nI\nCH. 1-0432\nCH. 1-0069\ni expiration date of the old con-'\ntract between Retail Associates\nand the union.\n3. Job restoration for all strik\ners, without coercion.\u201d\nAt the meeting Mr. DeLong\nrepresented UAW Vice Presi\ndent Richard T. Gosser who was\nout of town.\nCamp Dates\nContinued from Page 1\nAmong shops which have\nbeen heard from are Willys, To\nledo Stamping, Save Electric,\nIndustrial\nFinishers,\nBarrett,\nBuddies, Champion, Dana, Auto\nLite and Continental Aviation.\nFor the benefit of those who\nmay have missed the previous\nannouncement of camping dates,\nthe Journal is reprinting this\nyear\u2019s Local 12 Summer Camp\nschedule:\nBOYS\nLeave\n1st week June 22\n2nd week June 29\n3rd week July 6\n4th\n5th\nweek\nJuly 13\n1st\nweek July 20\nGIRLS\nLeave\nweek July 27\nReturn\nJune 28\nJuly 5\nJuly 12\nJuly 19\nJuly 26\n2nd week\nAug.\n3rd week Aug. 10\n4th week Aug. 17\n5th week Aug. 24\nReturn\nAug. 2\nAug. 9\nAug. 15\nAug. 23\nAug. 30\n3\nC of C Head Finds\nRecession Solace\nThe new president of the\nU. S. Chamber of Com\nmerce has found a silver\nlining in the current reces\nsion.\nWilliam A. McDonnell,\nboard chairman of the First\nNational Bank in St. Louis\nsaid the recession would in\ncrease productivity because\n\u201cjobs are treasured more\nand most people work a lit\ntle harder.\n$207\n2\nFete\nUniteast Local Signs Up To Use Willys Clinic\nThe 90th Local Union or Unit to affiliate\nwith the Willys Unit Diagnostic Clinic was\nLocal 48, Unitcast, whose executive com\nmittee is shown here signing the contract.\nSeated are Francis Counts (left), Joe Wlo\ndarz, president, and George Heltz. Stand*\nRecession\nContinued from Page 1\nsupport of the AFL-CIO pro\ngram. He urged also the elimina\ntion of the present 10 per cent\nexcise tax on passenger travel\nand 3 per cent on freight.\nCarl Megel, president of the\nAmerican Federation of Teach\ners, urged immediate action by\nCongress on a schol construction\nprogram and an income tax cut.\nThe American recession ap\np a r e n 11 y was having its\ncounter-part in Canada with\n834,544 persons registered for\nunemployment insurance or\n20 per cent of the insured\nwork force.\nThe Dominion Bureau of Sta\ntistics reported that average\nweekly wages and hours were\ndown in Januagy.\n\u2014Union Journal photo\ning are (left to right) Jesse Mitchell, Percy\nTaylor, Dan Grycza, James Ellis, Robert\nFlorence and William Mitchell. Absent\nwhen picture was taken was Lutus Willey\nand Floyd Greiser.\nGIVE\nYOURSELF\nA GOOD\nBRAKE\nBy The\nExperts\nTURNER\nBRAKE SERVICE\n11 l-14th St. CH. 3-8255\nSEWER (LOWED? Cl\nYour I\nROTO-ROOTER\nService Mon\nGH 4-4871\nFree Estimates\nAll Sewer Jobs\nGuaranteed 2 Years\n23 Years Satisfied Service\n1713 DETROIT AVENUE\nYou see so many different kinds of programs for meet\ning hospital bills these days, but no one seems to under\nstand the real needs of the people the way Blue Cross does.\nBlue Cross protection is really different\u2014more practical.\nIt aims to help in terms of hospital care and the services\nyou really need when hospitalized.\nBlue Cross gives you more-for'your dollar because it is\na non-profit plan. Every cent paid in except for necessary\nexpenses, goes toward paying for subscribers' hospital care.\n95c out of every $1 was returned to the subscribed in 1957\nin the form of PAID hospital bills.\nTo get the best, why not consult your employer about e\ngroup program. Persons who are under 65, in good health,\nand self-employed, or working where fewer than 10 persons\nare employed are eligible for non-group enrollment. Call\nCHerry, 4-9531.\nmom.\nHELPS PAY\nHOSPITAL BILLS\nBIVES/HEID.\nHELPS PAY\nDOCTOR BILLS\nThe Hospital Service Association of Toledo\nOhio Medical Indemnity, Inc.\n2139 Madison Ave.\nI\nToledo 2, Ohio","height":"26916","width":"19692"}}
